******
[1] National
Date: Wed 7 Mar 2018
Source: Secretariat of Health Surveillance, Ministry of Health [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://portalms.saude.gov.br/noticias/agencia-saude/42717-febre-amarela-ministerio-da-saude-atualiza-casos-no-pais-07-03

Brazil confirmed 846 cases and 260 deaths for the period 1 Jul 2017 - 6 Mar of this year [2018]. During the same period last year there were 597 confirmed cases and 190 deaths.

This [Wed 7 Mar 2018] the Ministry of Health updated the information sent in by the state secretariats of health about the yellow fever situation in the country. During the monitoring period [1 Jul 2017 to 6 Mar 2018] there were 846 confirmed cases of yellow fever in the country that led to 260 deaths. In total, during this period there were 3234 reported suspected cases, of which 1560 were discarded and 828 remain under investigation.

Last year from [1 Jul 2016 to 28 Feb 2017], there were there were 597 confirmed cases and 190 confirmed deaths. These reports of yellow fever cases show a pattern of disease seasonality, occurring mainly in summer, with the period of analysis considered to be [1 Jul-30 Jun] of each year.

Although the number of cases of the current monitoring period have been higher than during the previous season, yellow fever today circulates in metropolitan regions of the country that have the greatest contingent of the population, hitting 32.5 million, including people who live in areas that never had recommendations for [yellow fever] vaccination. In the past season, for example, the outbreak hit a population [at risk] of 8.4 million people. This explains why the incidence of the disease in this period is lower than in the past period. The incidence of the disease in the monitoring period until [6 Mar 2018] is 2.4 cases for 100 000 inhabitants. In the past season, 2016/2017, the incidence was 7/100 000 inhabitants, in the same period [but with a smaller population at risk].

Campaign
--------
To increase vaccine coverage, the states of Rio de Janeiro and Sao Paulo decided to continue the strategy of vaccination of the population. This effort counts on the help of the Ministry of Health. Preliminary data from the Secretariats of Health of the states of Bahia, Rio de Janeiro and Sao Paulo to the Ministry of Health indicates that as of [6 Mar 2018], 17.3 million people were vaccinated, including cumulative numbers of the public vaccinated in the municipalities. The number corresponds to 76 percent of the number targeted for the campaign. The Ministry of Health emphasizes the importance of vaccinating the population in the states of Rio de Janeiro, Bahia and São Paulo during the campaign against yellow fever. According to the data sent in to the Ministry of Health by the states, as of [6 Mar 2018] 8.4 million people (90 percent) were vaccinated in Sao Paulo and 7.1 million (71.5 percent) in Rio de Janeiro. Currently in the state of Bahia, 1.8 million people were vaccinated for a total of 55 percent of the targeted public.

