Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Cases of yellow fever (YF) continue to increase, albeit slowly. The YF vaccination campaign has been catching up quickly to the targeted coverage. The above report provides a good update on the current yellow fever (YF) situation in Brazil. There is no indication that the outbreak has ended. Although there have been no reports of cases from the urban, _Aedes aegypti_, cycle of transmission the risk remains that spill-over from the sylvan (forest) cycle could occur. _Aedes aegypti_ vector mosquitoes are present in the area and responsible for the transmission of dengue, Zika and chikungunya viruses. It is important to note that cases of YF in humans and monkeys are occurring in areas outside of the 3 states where the outbreak is occurring. There is risk of new human cases and outbreaks in other areas, so that surveillance in a broad area of Brazil is important.

Maps of Brazil can be accessed at http://s13.postimg.org/jumnalk87/map_of_Brazil.gif and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5674952,6. - Mod.TY]

******
[2] Vale do Ribeira, São Paulo state
Date: Sat 3 Mar 2018, 9:00 PM
Source: G1 [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
https://g1.globo.com/sp/santos-regiao/noticia/macaco-com-virus-da-febre-amarela-e-encontrado-morto-no-vale-do-ribeira-sp.ghtml


The Pedro de Toledo municipal administration in the Vale do Ribeira region, in the interior of Sao Paulo [state] , confirmed on this [Fri 2 Mar 2018]) the presence of yellow fever virus in a monkey that was found dead in the limits with the city of Iguape. Residents of nearby regions have to be vaccinated against this expected disease.

According to the issued information, the monkey was found in the Despraiado neighborhood. Given its proximity to the neighboring city, a team from the Pedro de Toledo government collected it to carry out tests. The result came out this week and confirmed the presence of the virus in the animal, whose species was not given.

Both municipalities declared special attention to the locality. Residents of the area who have not been vaccinated are targets of a task force for immunization to occur. According to information from the Health agencies, there are no registered cases of yellow fever among the residents of the 2 cities.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[This was predictable. After identifying circulation of yellow fever virus in the Baixada Santista, it is more than expected that the virus spread not by the green corridors, but by the "green avenue" that is the Atlantic Forest to the Ribeira Valley. The identification of the virus in the Ribeira Valley ratifies the importance (necessity) of the expansion of the vaccination recommendation areas in the state of São Paulo. A previous 2018 post stated, "As important as the increasing number of confirmed cases (and deaths) of yellow fever in the state of São Paulo is the apparent progressive expansion of virus (and transmission) circulation to different areas of the state including the coastal regions. The current scenario further ratifies not only the importance of intensifying vaccination strategies in areas where the recommendation is already in force but the need to plan the rapid incorporation of the recommendation for yellow fever vaccination in every state."

The Ribeira Valley is a region located in the south of the state of São Paulo and in the eastern state of Paraná, Brazil. It is named after the river basin of the Ribeira de Iguape River and the Lagunar Estuary of Iguape, Cananeia and Paranaguá. Its area of 2 830 666 hectares [1092926 sq mi] is home to a population of 481 224 inhabitants and fully includes the area of 31 municipalities (9 from Paraná and 22 from São Paulo). There are also 21 other municipalities in the state of Paraná and another 18 municipalities in the state of São Paulo, which are partially included in the Ribeira basin. It houses 61 percent of the Atlantic Forest remaining in Brazil, 150 000 hectares [57 915 sq mi] of restinga [coastal tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forest] and 17 000 [6563 sq mi] of mangroves (Source: https://pt.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vale_do_Ribeira. - Mod.RNA

This case of YF in a dead monkey in a new locality underscores the importance of local surveillance support by rapid laboratory-based diagnosis as a basis for focused vaccination efforts. - Mod.TY]
